    <content>&lt;p dir="ltr" style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/octae-icon-keyideasforward.png" alt="" width="140" height="136" role="presentation" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_middle"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Unlike children, adults do not
have time to spend several hours a day learning to read. In fact, many adults
will struggle to attend class at all. Educators can increase the likelihood
that adults will persist with reading when the content is information they can
use or care about. Reminding adults that they are probably already engaged in
reading basic material like&amp;nbsp;recipes, signs, texts, or bills is a great
